text: Germany invades Denmark, they capitulate after two hours
Baltic States were annexed by USSR
Romania was taken over by pro-Nazi "Ironguard" forces
Bulgaria annexed a region of Southern Romania
Germany captures Minsk in the USSR (modern Belarus)
Germany captures Kiev in the USSR (modern Ukraine)
Germany begins a siege of Leningrad
Russian mud season (Rasputitsa) begins, greatly slowing Nazi advance
German troops are a mere 19 miles from Red Square in Moscow
Germans halt advance, Soviets launch first successful counterattack and begin beating Germans back
Hitler sacks 37 of his top commanders for failure in USSR
Soviets retake Kiev in the Ukraine
Soviets relieve Leningrad after nearly 900 days under siege
Allies launch D-Day and land in Northern France
Romania leaves the Axis and declares war on Nazi Germany
Battle of the Bulge begins as Germans attempt last ditch Western offensive
Allies liberate Buchenwald and President Roosevelt dies
Mussolini is captured and hanged by partisans in Northen Italy

The Nazis invade Poland with the Soviet Union and the country is divided between Nazi Germany in the West and the Soviet Union in the East; Lenin falls under Soviet occupation. 
"For the time being, the Soviet Union assumed control of the eastern side of the country, and the Nazis occupied the western side. Poland, as we had known it, no longer existed. We found ourselves under Soviet rule" (51).

Nazi forces attacked Soviet-occupied Poland and the Soviet Union "That night a strange commotion woke me up...For the first time, I felt the penetrating bitterness and horror of war. Little did I know there was far worse to come" (63-64).

The Nazis created a ghetto in Lenin. 
"With no advance warning, they forced the Jewish population out of their own homes and into an old Jewish part of town in an area as small as two city blocks. Fifty to sixty people were crowded into each small house. Close to two thousand people were crammed into those few houses."

Faye is told to leave her camera at Gestapo headquarters.
"The Nazis knew the next morning would be our last" (85) 


The Jewish ghetto in Lenin is liquidated; 1850 Jews are murdered, shot and buried in three mass graves. Faye is one of 27 people who survive this massacre.
"All were killed and buried in those three long trenches, including my father, my mother, my little brother Boruch and both my sisters Sonia and Esther, Esther's husband, as well as Sonia's two children... The Nazis did not waste bullets on children...One thousand eight hundred and fifty Jewish people were executed..."
Faye is briefly reunited with her brother Kopel, who also joined a partisan group
The town of Lenin is razed by the Nazis, and the remaining non-Jewish population is burned to death.
Soviet Troops liberate the Molotava Brigade's territory and the Nazis are driven out. The partisans liberate the city of Pinsk.
